Cersanit, PBG, PGE, Tauron: Central European Equity Preview

-- B y   M a c i e j   M a r t e w i c z
-- 
2011-03-22T03:59:59Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-03-22/cersanit-pbg-pge-tauron-central-european-equity-preview.html
The following is a list of
companies whose shares may have unusual price changes in central
European markets. Stock symbols are in parentheses after company
names. Share prices are from the last close.  Poland ’s WIG20 Index rose 0.5 percent and the Czech PX
Index added 1 percent.  Hungary ’s BUX Index climbed 1.8 percent.  Cersanit SA (CST)  : Poland’s biggest ceramic tilemaker
said today its net income reached 103.2 million zloty ($36.4
million) in 2010, reversing a net loss of 8.13 million zloty the
year before. The figure was below the 123.2 million-zloty mean
estimate of five analysts surveyed by Bloomberg. Cersanit fell
2.2 percent to 12.31 zloty.  Magyar Telekom Nyrt. (MTEL HB): Hungary’s National Bureau
of Investigation terminated a probe into alleged
misappropriation of funds at Hungary’s former phone monopoly
controlled by Deutsche Telekom AG after finding no evidence.
Telekom gained 2.8 percent to 590 forint.  Mostostal Warszawa SA (MSW)  : The Polish construction
company and a unit of  Spain ’s Acciona SA said its 2010 net
income fell to 61.8 million zloty from 117.3 million zloty in
2009. That compares with the 67.3 million-zloty mean estimate in
a Bloomberg survey of five analysts. The stock gained 3.1
percent to 44.35 zloty.  PBG SA (PBG)  : Poland’s largest construction company by
market value will report its 2010 earnings. PBG lost 1.6 percent
to 194.5 zloty.  PGE SA (PGE PW): Poland’s largest power utility is
scheduled to publish 2010 earnings. PGE gained 0.4 percent to
23.05 zloty.  Synthos SA (SNS)  : A Polish producer of chemicals said
2010 net income rose to 476.2 million zloty from 164.2 million
zloty a year earlier. That beat the 418.3 million-zloty mean
estimate of four analysts surveyed by Bloomberg. Synthos gained
1.2 percent to 4.13 zloty.  Tauron Polska Energia SA (TPE)  : The Polish government is
selling up to 209 million shares, or 11.9 percent, in its
second-largest utility, according to terms of the offer obtained
by Bloomberg News. Tauron fell 1.1 percent to 6.39 zloty.  To contact the reporter on this story:
